This makes maximum value dynamic and treats value as value, rather than percentage. I did this because it felt right, basically.

By default, progressbar behaves like it has before: if you only supply value, max defaults to 100 and value can be treated as a percentage. If you change max, you can use percentage to set/retrieve the percentage of value/max.

I also moved the change event trigger to _refreshValue, made it track it's oldValue and only fire when the value has been changed

I use it like this (moved the display portion out of jquery-ui):

```
<div class="progress-bar" data-value="50" data-max="500"></div>

updateProgressDisplay = function() {
    var display = "<span class='ui-progressbar-content'>" + $(this).progressbar('value') + '/' + $(this).progressbar('max') + ' (' + $(this).progressbar('percentage').toFixed(0) + '%)</span>';
    $(this).children('.ui-progressbar-value').html(display);
}

$('.progress-bar').each(function(){
    $(this).progressbar({
        value: parseInt($(this).attr('data-value')),
        max: parseInt($(this).attr('data-max')),
        change: updateProgressDisplay,
        create: updateProgressDisplay
    });
})  
```
